    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Beyond pH, there are a few other sneaky things that can act like tiny, hungry little goblins, stealing nutrients from your tomatoes! One major culprit is root rot, which is essentially a fungal invasion that chokes the roots, preventing them from absorbing anything, even if the soil is perfectly balanced. Another possibility is a pest infestation, like spider mites or aphids, which suck the life right out of the leaves, leaving them pale and weakened. It's always good to inspect the undersides of those leaves—you might find tiny, unwelcome guests hiding there, just like a sneaky little bandit trying to steal your hard-earned snacks.",
